Trade union Hospersa is calling on the KZN health department to withdraw plans to loan community health workers to schools. The union says the health workers should continue assisting home-based patients in ensuring they don't default on their medication. Courtesy of #DStv403 DURBAN - Trade union Hospersa is calling on the KZN health department to withdraw plans to loan community health workers to schools. This is part of the education department's school readiness plan. READ: KZN education department refutes unions' claims on school readiness The union says the health workers should continue assisting home-based patients in ensuring they don't default on their medication. Hospersa's Kevin Halama said they are attempting to contact the department in an attempt to persuade them to retract the statement and consult with the union before redeploying the healthcare workers to schools on Monday. READ: 90% of schools will be ready to reopen next week: DoE Halama said the health workers usually assist acute home-based patients and patients who need help accessing their chronic medication. He said the Department of Education would be creating a void in the primary healthcare services in the province. READ: COVID-19: PPE stolen from school districts in KZN Halama said until the health department engages with labour representatives, community healthcare workers would continue carrying out their usual duties. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday. Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.